The shell hash at the top of the core is likely caved in material during coring.  In the shell hash are fragments of Tawara, Stiracolpus, barnacles, echinoid spines.

The muddy sand is moderately sorted, vf-f (mostly vf) micaceous, slightly calcareous sand. This lithology contains abundant shell fragments of mostly bivalve Tawera scattered throughout. This interval also contains large fragments of Crassostrea(?), barnacles and scaphopods.  Half of a greywacke pebble (3.4 cm (estimated) x 2.6 cm x 1.2 cm, L:I:S axes) with pitting and abrasion on the surface is found at 95-98 cm.

The shell hash at the top of the core is likely caved in material during coring.  In the shell hash are fragments of Tawara, Stiracolpus, barnacles, echinoid spines.  The shell hash is muddy frm 33-47 cm.
The muddy sand is moderately sorted, vf-f (mostly vf) micaceous sand. This lithology contains abundant shell fragments of mostly bivalve scattered throughout.

The muddy sand is well sorted, vf-f (mostly vf) micaceous sand. This lithology contains abundant shell fragments of mostly bivalve scattered throughout.  36-41 cm and 67-39  is soft/soupy and is likely disturbance from drilling.
